fn_tests.input_infer:
1. For visitor.visit_pre(ast) to be Ok/Some: ast = Ast::Literal(Literal), expects valid input for literal characters.
2. For self.induct(ast, &mut visitor) to be Ok/Some: ast = Ast::Repetition(Repetition), requires non-empty repetitions.
3. For let Some(x) = self.induct(ast, &mut visitor) to be true: ast = Ast::Group(Group), needs a valid group structure.
4. For visitor.visit_post(ast) to be Ok/Some: ast = Ast::Concat(Concat), ensuring all children are processed.
5. For self.stack.pop() to match Some((post_ast, frame)) to be true: stack is initially populated with valid frames from ast.
6. For let Some(x) = self.pop(frame) to be true: frame must be of type Frame::Alternation.
7. For let Frame::Alternation {..} = x to be true: x must be constructed as Frame::Alternation with at least one child node.
8. For visitor.visit_alternation_in() to be Ok/Some: alternation must contain valid expressions.
9. For visitor.visit_pre(ast)? to be Err/None: ast = Ast::Empty(Span) or a similar structure that results in visit_pre returning an error.

Valid test input ranges could be:
Ast::Literal(Literal) when character set is a-z, Ast::Repetition(Repetition) with range of 1 to 5, Ast::Group(Group) with nested structures, Ast::Concat(Concat) with 1 to 3 valid child expressions, Ast::Alternation { head: &Ast::Literal(Literal), tail: &[] } confirming valid alternative scenarios.
